[Event "Baker Bridge - Jacoby Transfers"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "N:T5.KQT4.AK7.KQ98 J762.8.652.75432 KQ94.AJ973.83.A6 A83.652.QJT94.JT"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
1NT pass 2D pass 3H pass 4C pass 4D pass 6H all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "d47989381a251976a82c05494feaa37802b1d4a3061fd82e01ea1f74b620878a"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/jacoby_transfers"]
[Student "S"]
{You open 1NT and partner responds 2\D.  

Just hold it a minute and DO NOT say 2\H. True, when partner transfers, you <b>almost</b> always just obey and complete the transfer. This is the one time when you don't. You had a 17 point 1NT opener with 4 \Hs and a doubleton. As soon as partner told you to bid \Hs your hand became worth 18 points because of the good trump support and the doubleton. So you inform partner of this by making the "super-accept" bid of 3\H. In other words, you complete the transfer with a jump. 

Partner's eyes get big (but you aren't allowed to notice that) and he bids 4\C.

Partner's \C bid was not a suit, you already have an agreed suit, \Hs. The \C bid was showing you first round control in \Cs, and is a slam try by partner.

You continue the search for slam by showing your first round \D control, you bid 4\D. 

That was all partner needed to hear, he jumps straight to 6\H.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "E:JT4.AK.AK97.KQ98 62.QT53.QJ53.T64 Q9853.72.8642.A3 AK7.J9864.T.J752"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2NT pass 3H pass 3S pass 3NT pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "4209d3ca1f6b4dadbf678e5fb9c8e1b677fc1766ad8d52e4fa20e6ca90e2e4db"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/jacoby_transfers"]
[Student "S"]
{You open 2NT and partner responds 3\H.  

You bid 3\S, just as partner asked. He puts you in game at 3NT.  Bid or pass? 

Bid of course. You have an 8-card \S fit so you prefer \Ss to notrump.

As you can see, 3NT would surely go down with a \H lead, while 4\S is cold.

One hand doesn't mean it will always be like this, but usually if you have an 8-card fit the Major suit game will be better than 3NT.}

